Haas have offered no clarity over Nikita Mazepin's Formula One future amid Russia's invasion of eastern Ukraine. Haas team boss Guenther Steiner was coy about the future of Mazepin, whose seat is funded by Russian oligarch father Dimitry, at a press conference on Friday.  Tensions between Russia and Ukraine escalated on Wednesday when president Vladimir Putin launched a devastating attack on Ukraine. And on Friday, Haas team principal Steiner was asked about Mazepin's future. JUST IN: Russia Grand Prix axed from 2022 schedule as F1 chiefs respond Mazepin's seat is funded by his Russian oligarch father Dimitry, who runs Uralkali. Mazepin Snr has frequently been seen with president Putin and the company is at risk of sanctions. “Unfortunately, we had an oil leak and we could not do a lot of laps. He plans to be in Bahrain, so there is no change on that one. The decision came following mouting pressure from drivers, including Sebastien Vettel, who said they would consider boycotting the event over Russia's invasion of Ukraine. An F1 statement read: "The FIA Formula 1 World Championship visits countries all over the world with a positive vision to unite people, bringing nations together. "We are watching the developments in Ukraine with sadness and shock and hope for a swift and peaceful resolution to the present situation. "On Thursday evening Formula 1, the FIA, and the teams discussed the position of our sport, and the conclusion is, including the view of all relevant stakeholders, that it is impossible to hold the Russian Grand Prix in the current circumstances."   